{"cursor":"19883","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Halomethane' compounds are derivatives of methane (CH 4) with one or\nmore of the hydrogen atoms replaced with halogen atoms (F, Cl, Br, or I).\nHalomethanes are both naturally occurring, especially in marine environments,\nand man-made, most notably as refrigerants, solvents, propellants, and\nfumigants. Many, including the chlorofluorocarbons, have attracted wide\nattention because they become active when exposed to ultraviolet light found at\nhigh altitudes and destroy the Earth's protective ozone layer.\n","linknr":480,"url":"Halomethanes","recorded":1362500053,"links":22,"instances":[],"pdf":["http://www.oehha.ca.gov/water/phg/pdf/dcm.pdf","http://www.oehha.ca.gov/water/phg/pdf/dcm.pdf"],"categories":["Aerosol propellants","DuPont","Greenhouse gases","Halogenated solvents","Halomethanes|","Heating, ventilating, and air conditioning","Refrigerants","Fire suppression agents"],"headings":["Structure and properties","Production","Classes of compounds","Applications","Safety","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[],"members":[],"related":["Methane","Hydrogen","Halogen","Fluorine","Chlorine","Bromine","Iodine","Chlorofluorocarbon","Ultraviolet_light","Ozone_layer","Natural_gas","Methanol","Halogen","Halogenation","Biosynthesis","Chloroperoxidase","Bromoperoxidase","Hydrochlorofluorocarbon","Fluorocarbon","Perfluorocarbon","Freon","Refrigeration","Trademark","DuPont","Greenhouse_gas","Global_warming","Kyoto_Protocol","Environmental_Investigation_Agency","Carbon_tetrachloride","Tetrabromomethane","Carbon_tetraiodide","Tetrafluoromethane","Chloromethane","Dichloromethane","Chloroform","Trichlorofluoromethane","Dichlorodifluoromethane","Chlorotrifluoromethane","C